# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bqn-array
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] In computer science, **array programming** refers to solutions that allow the application of operations to an entire set of values at once.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Such solutions are commonly used in scientific and engineering settings.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Modern programming languages that support array programming (also known as vector or multidimensional languages) have been engineered specifically to generalize operations on scalars to apply transparently to vectors, matrices, and higher-dimensional arrays.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] These include APL, J, Fortran, MATLAB, Analytica, Octave, PL/I, R, Cilk Plus, Julia, Perl Data Language (PDL) and Raku.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] In these languages, an operation that operates on entire arrays can be called a *vectorized* operation, regardless of whether it is executed on a vector processor, which implements vector instructions.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Array programming primitives concisely express broad ideas about data manipulation.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The level of concision can be dramatic in certain cases: it is not uncommon to find array programming language one-liners that require several pages of object-oriented code.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The fundamental idea behind array programming is that operations apply at once to an entire set of values.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] This makes it a high-level programming model as it allows the programmer to think and operate on whole aggregates of data, without having to resort to explicit loops of individual scalar operations.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The basis behind array programming and thinking is to find and exploit the properties of data where individual elements are similar or adjacent.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Unlike object orientation which implicitly breaks down data to its constituent parts (or scalar quantities), array orientation looks to group data and apply a uniform handling.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Function rank is an important concept to array programming languages in general, by analogy to tensor rank in mathematics: functions that operate on data may be classified by the number of dimensions they act on.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Ordinary multiplication, for example, is a scalar ranked function because it operates on zero-dimensional data (individual numbers).
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The cross product operation is an example of a vector rank function because it operates on vectors, not scalars.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Matrix multiplication is an example of a 2-rank function, because it operates on 2-dimensional objects (matrices).
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Collapse operators reduce the dimensionality of an input data array by one or more dimensions.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] For example, summing over elements collapses the input array by 1 dimension.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Array programming is very well suited to implicit parallelization; a topic of much research nowadays.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Further, Intel and compatible CPUs developed and produced after 1997 contained various instruction set extensions, starting from MMX and continuing through SSSE3 and 3DNow!, which include rudimentary SIMD array capabilities.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] This has continued into the 2020s with instruction sets such as AVX-512, making modern CPUs sophisticated vector processors.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Array processing is distinct from parallel processing in that one physical processor performs operations on a group of items simultaneously while parallel processing aims to split a larger problem into smaller ones (MIMD) to be solved piecemeal by numerous processors.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Processors with multiple cores and GPUs with thousands of general computing cores are common as of 2023.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The canonical examples of array programming languages are Fortran, APL, and J.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Others include: A+, Analytica, Chapel, IDL, Julia, K, Klong, Q, MATLAB, GNU Octave, Scilab, FreeMat, Perl Data Language (PDL), R, Raku, S-Lang, SAC, Nial, ZPL, Futhark, and TI-BASIC.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] In scalar languages such as C and Pascal, operations apply only to single values, so *a*+*b* expresses the addition of two numbers.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] In such languages, adding one array to another requires indexing and looping, the coding of which is tedious.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Some C compilers like GCC at some optimization levels detect and vectorize sections of code that its heuristics determine would benefit from it.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Another approach is given by the OpenMP API, which allows one to parallelize applicable sections of code by taking advantage of multiple CPU cores.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] In array languages, operations are generalized to apply to both scalars and arrays.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Thus, *a*+*b* expresses the sum of two scalars if *a* and *b* are scalars, or the sum of two arrays if they are arrays.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] An array language simplifies programming but possibly at a cost known as the *abstraction penalty*.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Because the additions are performed in isolation from the rest of the coding, they may not produce the optimally most efficient code.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The previous C code would become the following in the Ada language, which supports array-programming syntax.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] APL uses single character Unicode symbols with no syntactic sugar.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] This operation works on arrays of any rank (including rank 0), and on a scalar and an array.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Analytica provides the same economy of expression as Ada.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Dartmouth BASIC had MAT statements for matrix and array manipulation in its third edition (1966).
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Stata's matrix programming language Mata supports array programming.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Below, we illustrate addition, multiplication, addition of a matrix and a scalar, element by element multiplication, subscripting, and one of Mata's many inverse matrix functions.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The implementation in MATLAB allows the same economy allowed by using the Fortran language.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Both MATLAB and GNU Octave natively support linear algebra operations such as matrix multiplication, matrix inversion, and the numerical solution of system of linear equations, even using the Moore–Penrose pseudoinverse.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The Nial example of the inner product of two arrays can be implemented using the native matrix multiplication operator.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] If `a` is a row vector of size [1 n] and `b` is a corresponding column vector of size [n 1].
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The rasdaman query language is a database-oriented array-programming language.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The R language supports array paradigm by default.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] Raku supports the array paradigm via its Metaoperators.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The following example demonstrates the addition of arrays @a and @b using the Hyper-operator in conjunction with the plus operator.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The matrix left-division operator concisely expresses some semantic properties of matrices.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] As in the scalar equivalent, if the (determinant of the) coefficient (matrix) `A` is not null then it is possible to solve the (vectorial) equation `A * x = b` by left-multiplying both sides by the inverse of `A`: `A−1` (in both MATLAB and GNU Octave languages: `A^-1`).
