[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The previous statements are also valid MATLAB expressions if the third one is executed before the others (numerical comparisons may be false because of round-off errors).
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] However, these solutions are neither the most concise ones (e.g. still remains the need to notationally differentiate overdetermined systems) nor the most computationally efficient.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The latter point is easy to understand when considering again the scalar equivalent `a * x = b`, for which the solution `x = a^-1 * b` would require two operations instead of the more efficient `x = b / a`.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] This is not only an example of terse array programming from the coding point of view but also from the computational efficiency perspective, which in several array programming languages benefits from quite efficient linear algebra libraries such as ATLAS or LAPACK.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] The use of specialized and efficient libraries to provide more terse abstractions is also common in other programming languages.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] In C++ several linear algebra libraries exploit the language's ability to overload operators.
[src:bqn-array/array-programming] In some cases a very terse abstraction in those languages is explicitly influenced by the array programming paradigm, as the NumPy extension library to Python, Armadillo and Blitz++ libraries do.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Combinatory logic was originally intended as a 'pre-logic' that would clarify the role of quantified variables in logic, essentially by eliminating them.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Another way of eliminating quantified variables is Quine's predicate functor logic.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] While the expressive power of combinatory logic typically exceeds that of first-order logic, the expressive power of predicate functor logic is identical to that of first-order logic (Quine 1960, 1966, 1976).
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The inventor of combinatory logic, Moses Schönfinkel, published nothing on combinatory logic after his original 1924 paper.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Haskell Curry rediscovered the combinators while working as an instructor at Princeton University in late 1927.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] In the late 1930s, Alonzo Church and his students at Princeton invented a rival formalism for functional abstraction, the lambda calculus, which proved more popular than combinatory logic.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The upshot of these historical contingencies was that until theoretical computer science began taking an interest in combinatory logic in the 1960s and 1970s, nearly all work on the subject was by Haskell Curry and his students, or by Robert Feys in Belgium.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Curry and Feys (1958), and Curry *et al.* (1972) survey the early history of combinatory logic.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] For a more modern treatment of combinatory logic and the lambda calculus together, see the book by Barendregt, which reviews the models Dana Scott devised for combinatory logic in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] In computer science, combinatory logic is used as a simplified model of computation, used in computability theory and proof theory.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Despite its simplicity, combinatory logic captures many essential features of computation.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Combinatory logic can be viewed as a variant of the lambda calculus, in which lambda expressions (representing functional abstraction) are replaced by a limited set of *combinators*, primitive functions without free variables.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] It is easy to transform lambda expressions into combinator expressions, and combinator reduction is much simpler than lambda reduction.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Hence combinatory logic has been used to model some non-strict functional programming languages and hardware.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The purest form of this view is the programming language Unlambda, whose sole primitives are the S and K combinators augmented with character input/output.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Although not a practical programming language, Unlambda is of some theoretical interest.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Combinatory logic can be given a variety of interpretations.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Many early papers by Curry showed how to translate axiom sets for conventional logic into combinatory logic equations.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Dana Scott in the 1960s and 1970s showed how to marry model theory and combinatory logic.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] where v is a variable name drawn from a predefined infinite set of variable names, and $E_{1}$ and $E_{2}$ are lambda-terms.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Terms of the form $\lambda v.E_{1}$ are called *abstractions*.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The variable v is called the formal parameter of the abstraction, and $E_{1}$ is the *body* of the abstraction.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The term $\lambda v.E_{1}$ represents the function which, applied to an argument, binds the formal parameter v to the argument and then computes the resulting value of $E_{1}$ — that is, it returns $E_{1}$ , with every occurrence of v replaced by the argument.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Terms of the form $E_{1}E_{2}$ are called *applications*.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Applications model function invocation or execution: the function represented by $E_{1}$ is to be invoked, with $E_{2}$ as its argument, and the result is computed.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] If $E_{1}$ (sometimes called the *applicand*) is an abstraction, the term may be *reduced*: $E_{2}$ , the argument, may be substituted into the body of $E_{1}$ in place of the formal parameter of $E_{1}$ , and the result is a new lambda term which is *equivalent* to the old one.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] If a lambda term contains no subterms of the form $((\lambda v.E_{1})E_{2})$ then it cannot be reduced, and is said to be in normal form.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The expression $E[v:=a]$ represents the result of taking the term E and replacing all free occurrences of v in it with a .
[src:bqn-array/combinator] By convention, we take $(abc)$ as shorthand for $((ab)c)$ (i.e., application is left associative).
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The motivation for this definition of reduction is that it captures the essential behavior of all mathematical functions.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] For example, consider the function that computes the square of a number.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] (Using " * " to indicate multiplication.) x here is the formal parameter of the function.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] To evaluate the resulting expression $3*3$ , we would have to resort to our knowledge of multiplication and the number 3.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Since any computation is simply a composition of the evaluation of suitable functions on suitable primitive arguments, this simple substitution principle suffices to capture the essential mechanism of computation.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Moreover, in lambda calculus, notions such as '3' and ' * ' can be represented without any need for externally defined primitive operators or constants.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] It is possible to identify terms in lambda calculus, which, when suitably interpreted, behave like the number 3 and like the multiplication operator, q.v.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Lambda calculus is known to be computationally equivalent in power to many other plausible models for computation (including Turing machines); that is, any calculation that can be accomplished in any of these other models can be expressed in lambda calculus, and vice versa.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] According to the Church–Turing thesis, both models can express any possible computation.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] It is perhaps surprising that lambda-calculus can represent any conceivable computation using only the simple notions of function abstraction and application based on simple textual substitution of terms for variables.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] But even more remarkable is that abstraction is not even required.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] *Combinatory logic* is a model of computation equivalent to lambda calculus, but without abstraction.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The advantage of this is that evaluating expressions in lambda calculus is quite complicated because the semantics of substitution must be specified with great care to avoid variable capture problems.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] In contrast, evaluating expressions in combinatory logic is much simpler, because there is no notion of substitution.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Since abstraction is the only way to manufacture functions in the lambda calculus, something must replace it in the combinatory calculus.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Instead of abstraction, combinatory calculus provides a limited set of primitive functions out of which other functions may be built.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The primitive functions are *combinators*, or functions that, when seen as lambda terms, contain no free variables.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] This is the same general convention (left-associativity) as for multiple application in lambda calculus.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] where E is a term mentioning only variables from the set $\{x_{1}\dots x_{n}\}$ .
[src:bqn-array/combinator] It is in this way that primitive combinators behave as functions.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] S applies x to y after first substituting z into each of them.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Or put another way, x is applied to y inside the environment z .
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Note that although $((S\,K\,K)\,x)=(Ix)$ for any x , $(S\,K\,K)$ itself is not equal to I .
[src:bqn-array/combinator] We say the terms are extensionally equal.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Extensional equality captures the mathematical notion of the equality of functions: that two functions are considered *equal* if they always produce the same results for the same arguments.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] In contrast, the terms themselves, together with the reduction of primitive combinators, capture the notion of *intensional equality* of functions: that two functions are considered *equal* only if they have identical implementations up to the expansion of primitive combinators.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] There are many ways to implement an identity function; $(S\,K\,K)$ and I are among these ways. $(S\,K\,S)$ is yet another.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] We will use the word *equivalent* to mean extensional equality.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] A more interesting combinator is the fixed point combinator or Y combinator, which can be used to implement recursion.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Note that *T*[ ] as given is not a well-typed mathematical function, but rather a term rewriter: Although it eventually yields a combinator, the transformation may generate intermediary expressions that are neither lambda terms nor combinators, via rule (5).
[src:bqn-array/combinator] This process is also known as *abstraction elimination*.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] This definition is exhaustive: any lambda expression will be subject to exactly one of these rules (see Summary of lambda calculus above).
[src:bqn-array/combinator] It is related to the process of *bracket abstraction*, which takes an expression *E* built from variables and application and produces a combinator expression [x]E in which the variable x is not free, such that [*x*]*E x* = *E* holds.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Bracket abstraction induces a translation from lambda terms to combinator expressions, by interpreting lambda-abstractions using the bracket abstraction algorithm.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] In general, the *T*[ ] construction may expand a lambda term of length *n* to a combinatorial term of length Θ(*n*3).
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The *T*[ ] transformation is motivated by a desire to eliminate abstraction.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Two special cases, rules 3 and 4, are trivial: *λx*.*x* is clearly equivalent to **I**, and *λx*.*E* is clearly equivalent to (**K** *T*[*E*]) if *x* does not appear free in *E*.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The first two rules are also simple: Variables convert to themselves, and applications, which are allowed in combinatory terms, are converted to combinators simply by converting the applicand and the argument to combinators.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] It is rules 5 and 6 that are of interest.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Rule 5 simply says that to convert a complex abstraction to a combinator, we must first convert its body to a combinator, and then eliminate the abstraction.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Rule 6 actually eliminates the abstraction.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] *E*1 and *E*2 each contain strictly fewer applications than (*E*1 *E*2), so the recursion must terminate in a lambda term with no applications at all—either a variable, or a term of the form *λx*.*E*.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] With the η-reduction rule, *λf*.*λx*.(*f* *x*) is transformed into **I**.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] There are one-point bases from which every combinator can be composed extensionally equal to *any* lambda term.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Since {**K**, **S**} is a basis, it follows that {**X**} is a basis too.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The Iota programming language uses **X** as its sole combinator.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] In fact, there exist infinitely many such bases.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] These combinators are extremely useful when translating predicate logic or lambda calculus into combinator expressions.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] They were also used by Curry, and much later by David Turner, whose name has been associated with their computational use.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The motivation here is that **B** and **C** are limited versions of **S**.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Whereas **S** takes a value and substitutes it into both the applicand and its argument before performing the application, **C** performs the substitution only in the applicand, and **B** only in the argument.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The modern names for the combinators come from Haskell Curry's doctoral thesis of 1930 (see B, C, K, W System).
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The reduction in combinator size that results from the new transformation rules can also be achieved without introducing **B** and **C**, as demonstrated in Section 3.2 of Tromp (2008).
[src:bqn-array/combinator] A distinction must be made between the **CL**K as described in this article and the **CL**I calculus.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The distinction corresponds to that between the λK and the λI calculus.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] As a consequence, combinator **K** is not present in the λI calculus nor in the **CL**I calculus.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The constants of **CL**I are: **I**, **B**, **C** and **S**, which form a basis from which all **CL**I terms can be composed (modulo equality).
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Every λI term can be converted into an extensionally equal **CL**I combinator according to rules similar to those presented above for the conversion of λK terms into **CL**K combinators.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Note, however, that this transformation is not the inverse transformation of any of the versions of *T*[ ] that we have seen.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] A normal form is any combinatory term in which the primitive combinators that occur, if any, are not applied to enough arguments to be simplified.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] It is undecidable whether a general combinatory term has a normal form; whether two combinatory terms are equivalent, etc.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] This can be shown in a similar way as for the corresponding problems for lambda terms.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The undecidable problems above (equivalence, existence of normal form, etc.) take as input syntactic representations of terms under a suitable encoding (e.g., Church encoding).
[src:bqn-array/combinator] One may also consider a toy trivial computation model where we "compute" properties of terms by means of combinators applied directly to the terms themselves as arguments, rather than to their syntactic representations.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] A predicate **N** is *nontrivial* if there are two arguments *A* and *B* such that **N** *A* = **T** and **N** *B* = **F**.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] A combinator **N** is *complete* if **N***M* has a normal form for every argument *M*.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] An analogue of Rice's theorem for this toy model then says that every complete predicate is trivial.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The proof of this theorem is rather simple.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Suppose there is a complete non trivial predicate, say **N**.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Hence (**N** ABSURDUM) is neither **T** nor **F**, which contradicts the presupposition that **N** would be a complete non trivial predicate.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] From this undefinability theorem it immediately follows that there is no complete predicate that can discriminate between terms that have a normal form and terms that do not have a normal form.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] If EQUAL would exist, then for all *A*, *λx.*(EQUAL *x A*) would have to be a complete non trivial predicate.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] This shows that definability by predicates is a not a reasonable model of decidability.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] David Turner used his combinators to implement the SASL programming language.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Iverson used primitives based on Curry's combinators in his J programming language, a successor to APL.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] This enabled what Iverson called tacit programming, that is, programming in functional expressions containing no variables, along with powerful tools for working with such programs.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] It turns out that tacit programming is possible in any APL-like language with user-defined operators.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The Curry–Howard isomorphism implies a connection between logic and programming: every proof of a theorem of intuitionistic logic corresponds to a reduction of a typed lambda term, and conversely.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Moreover, theorems can be identified with function type signatures.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Specifically, a typed combinatory logic corresponds to a Hilbert system in proof theory.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] The calculus consisting of **AK**, **AS**, and **MP** is complete for the implicational fragment of the intuitionistic logic, which can be seen as follows.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Consider the set *W* of all deductively closed sets of formulas, ordered by inclusion.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] This definition obeys the conditions on satisfaction of →: on one hand, if $X\Vdash A\to B$ , and $Y\in W$ is such that $Y\supseteq X$ and $Y\Vdash A$ , then $Y\Vdash B$ by modus ponens.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] On the other hand, if $X\not \Vdash A\to B$ , then $X,A\not \vdash B$ by the deduction theorem, thus the deductive closure of $X\cup \{A\}$ is an element $Y\in W$ such that $Y\supseteq X$ , $Y\Vdash A$ , and $Y\not \Vdash B$ .
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Let *A* be any formula which is not provable in the calculus.
[src:bqn-array/combinator] Then *A* does not belong to the deductive closure *X* of the empty set, thus $X\not \Vdash A$ , and *A* is not intuitionistically valid.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] In computer science, **function-level** programming refers to one of the two contrasting programming paradigms identified by John Backus in his work on programs as mathematical objects, the other being value-level programming.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] He designed FP to be the first programming language to specifically support the function-level programming style.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] A *function-level* program is **variable-free** (cf.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] *point-free* programming), since program variables, which are essential in value-level definitions, are not needed in function-level programs.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] In the function-level style of programming, a program is built directly from programs that are given at the outset, by combining them with **program-forming operations** or **functionals**.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] As a result, the function-level approach to programming invites study of the *space of programs under program-forming operations*, looking to derive useful algebraic properties of these program-forming operations.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] The function-level approach offers the possibility of making the set of programs a mathematical space by emphasizing the algebraic properties of the program-forming operations over the *space of programs*.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] Another potential advantage of the function-level view is the ability to use only strict functions and thereby have bottom-up semantics, which are the simplest kind of all.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] When Backus studied and publicized his function-level style of programming, his message was mostly misunderstood as supporting the traditional functional programming style languages instead of his own FP and its successor FL.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] Backus calls functional programming applicative programming; his function-level programming is a particular, constrained type.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] ...and the only way to generate new functions is to use one of the functional forms, which are fixed: you cannot build your own functional form (at least not within FP; you can within FFP (Formal FP)).
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] This restriction means that functions in FP are a module (generated by the built-in functions) over the algebra of functional forms, and are thus algebraically tractable.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] For instance, the general question of equality of two functions is equivalent to the halting problem, and is undecidable, but equality of two functions in FP is just equality in the algebra, and thus (Backus imagines) easier.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] Even today, many users of lambda style languages often misinterpret Backus' function-level approach as a restrictive variant of the lambda style, which is a *de facto* value-level style.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] The value-free style of FP is closely related to the equational logic of a cartesian-closed category.
[src:bqn-array/function-level-programming] The canonical function-level programming language is FP.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] All other functions are *first-order functions*.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] In mathematics higher-order functions are also termed *operators* or *functionals*.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] The differential operator in calculus is a common example, since it maps a function to its derivative, also a function.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Higher-order functions should not be confused with other uses of the word "functor" throughout mathematics, see Functor (disambiguation).
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] In the untyped lambda calculus, all functions are higher-order; in a typed lambda calculus, from which most functional programming languages are derived, higher-order functions that take one function as argument are values with types of the form $(\tau _{1}\to \tau _{2})\to \tau _{3}$ .
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] In the following examples, the higher-order function `twice` takes a function, and applies the function to some value twice.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] If `twice` has to be applied several times for the same `f` it preferably should return a function rather than a value.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] This is in line with the "don't repeat yourself" principle.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Alternatively, we can also compose using pure anonymous functions.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] In this Erlang example, the higher-order function `or_else/2` takes a list of functions (`Fs`) and argument (`X`).
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] It evaluates the function `F` with the argument `X` as argument.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] If the function `F` returns false then the next function in `Fs` will be evaluated.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] If the function `F` returns `{false, Y}` then the next function in `Fs` with argument `Y` will be evaluated.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] If the function `F` returns `R` the higher-order function `or_else/2` will return `R`.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Note that `X`, `Y`, and `R` can be functions.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Notice a function literal can be defined either with an identifier (`twice`) or anonymously (assigned to variable `plusThree`).
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Note that arrow functions implicitly capture any variables that come from the parent scope, whereas anonymous functions require the `use` keyword to do the same.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Python decorator syntax is often used to replace a function with the result of passing that function through a higher-order function.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] In Raku, all code objects are closures and therefore can reference inner "lexical" variables from an outer scope because the lexical variable is "closed" inside of the function.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Raku also supports "pointy block" syntax for lambda expressions which can be assigned to a variable or invoked anonymously.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Tcl uses apply command to apply an anonymous function (since 8.6).
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] The XACML standard defines higher-order functions in the standard to apply a function to multiple values of attribute bags.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] The list of higher-order functions in XACML can be found here.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Function pointers in languages such as C, C++, Fortran, and Pascal allow programmers to pass around references to functions.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] The qsort function from the C standard library uses a function pointer to emulate the behavior of a higher-order function.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Macros can also be used to achieve some of the effects of higher-order functions.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] However, macros cannot easily avoid the problem of variable capture; they may also result in large amounts of duplicated code, which can be more difficult for a compiler to optimize.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Macros are generally not strongly typed, although they may produce strongly typed code.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] In other imperative programming languages, it is possible to achieve some of the same algorithmic results as are obtained via higher-order functions by dynamically executing code (sometimes called *Eval* or *Execute* operations) in the scope of evaluation.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] In object-oriented programming languages that do not support higher-order functions, objects can be an effective substitute.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] An object's methods act in essence like functions, and a method may accept objects as parameters and produce objects as return values.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Objects often carry added run-time overhead compared to pure functions, however, and added boilerplate code for defining and instantiating an object and its method(s).
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] Languages that permit stack-based (versus heap-based) objects or structs can provide more flexibility with this method.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] The function `a()` takes a `Txy` record as input and returns the integer value of the sum of the record's `x` and `y` fields (3 + 7).
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] In this case, different types are used to trigger different functions via function overloading.
[src:bqn-array/higher-order-function] The overloaded function in this example has the signature `auto apply`.
